{
  "doc_id": "11661",
  "text": "A 1068 nucleotide region of a YHV sequence recently reported by [CITATION_1] was also analyzed. This sequence aligned with the GAV ORFlb gene upstream of and overlapping the 135 nucleotide sequence encompassed by the Thai primer pair 10F/144R (Wongteerasupaya et al. 1997) . Although there appears to be an insertion error at G408 which results in premature termination of the reading frame, the corrected sequence (excluding the overlap) shared 80.9% nucleotide and 86.5% amino acid sequence identity to GAV (Fig. 2c) . A comparison of all 3 ORFlb regions, the relative positions of which are shown in Fig. 3 , indicates that the overlapping 5' regions shared similar levels of sequence identity that were somewhat lower than that identified in the 3' helicase region, particularly at the amino acid level. In the helicase region amplified by primers GAV5 and GAV6, the level of sequence divergence between YHV and GAV is sirnilar to that observed within the same region of different strains (A59 and JHM) of murine coronaviruses [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Moreover, the ORFlb gene is likely to be more highly conserved than other genes encoding structural proteins, especially in those domains of ORFlb associated with enzymatic activity.",
